When people talk about why Indian Americans seem to do better overall than Chinese Americans, the debate online often gets lost in ideas about culture or national character. But if you go back to history and look at how the U.S. immigration system actually works, the explanation is quite straightforward: the success of Indian Americans today is mainly the result of the 1965 U.S. immigration reform.

The 1965 Immigration and Nationality Act is where everything starts. Before that, the U.S. basically welcomed only white European immigrants. Asians were very few and faced strict limits. After 1965, the U.S. began prioritizing high education and professional skills for immigration. For the first time, America opened its doors to skilled talent from around the world.

For India, this change was huge. Before 1965, there were only about ten thousand Indian immigrants in the whole country. After the reform, large numbers of highly educated doctors, engineers, and scholars came to the U.S. They became the foundation of the Indian American community, and their background shaped the groups overall education and income levels.

On the other hand, bc of The Cultural Revolution, the wave of highly educated, highly skilled Chinese immigrants didnt really start until the late 80s and early 90s, and it didnt reach its peak until the 2000s. Before that, the Chinese immigrant population was very mixed in background, came through many different pathways: early Chinese Americans born in the U.S., refugees from Southeast Asia, highly educated migrants from Taiwan, and later students and economic migrants from mainland China. This created a very diverse group with big differences in class and background. Chinese Americans were never a single filtered elite group, but a mix of many historical and political waves.

Because of this, Chinese Americans show a high peak + long tail pattern: many highly educated professionals, but also many who arrived as refugees or working-class migrants. This isnt about ability, its a result of different immigration routes.

Put simply, the differences we see today come from when and how each group came to the U.S., not from culture or talent, despite many people believe.
